column168: On 6/2/11 at approximately 1135 hours a Quality Carriers tank truck was starting to receive a load of methanol at IMTT.  There was approximately 60 gallons of methanol in the tanker compartment when the IMTT Operator discovered methanol dripping from the flange at the internal valve.  The IMTT Operator immediately shut down the system and secured the product line and truck valves.  A 5-gallon bucket was placed under the valve to collect the dripping methanol.  The remaining methanol in the tanker compartment was drained into a 55-gallon drum.  The truck was then released by IMTT so it could return to Quality Carriers for necessary repairs.
column169: IMTT-Bayonne contacted the customer of the product to inform them of the incident. The customer subsequently contacted the transportation company  and will address any mechanical or structural issues with the truck or related components.

column168: A van trailer at the intermediate truck transfer facility containing various hazardous waste shipments was to be unloaded for consolidation into other trailers destined for various disposal facilities.  The door was opened and a drum was found tipped over and leaking.  A response crew was notified, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and overpacked the drum into a suitable salvage container.  The trailer floor and area of containment directly beneath the trailer was cleaned with a suitable cleaning compount.  The cleanup material was placed into the salvage drum.  The State of Tennessee Emergency Management Authority was notified and assigned incident number 1532.
column169: The load was not properly blocked and braced.  It is felt that when the trailer backed over the containment berm that the drum shifted and tipped over.  The origin location was notified and was to discuss proper loading procedures with all dock personnel.

column168: A shipment of hazardous waste was at the intermediate truck transfer facility for consolidation onto a trailer destined for the intended waste disposal facility.  A small leak was found near the bottom chime of one drum.  A response crew was notified, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and the drum was overpacked into a suitable salvage drum along with the absorbent material used to clean up the spill.  The drum was then loaded onto the container without further incident.
column169: The drums showed no sign of leaking when picked up.  However the supervisor felt that the driver could have inspected the drums more carefully for signs of deterioration.  The incident was discussed with the driver by the operations manager.

column168: A van trailer containing multiple shipments of hazardous waste was being unloaded at the intermediate truck transfer facility for consolidation into other trailers for various destinations.  Liquid was found to be leaking from a 350 gallon tote container.  A response crew was notified, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment, and entered the trailer.  A hole was found in the side of the tote that had been patched with some sort of material that did not hold and leaked.  The contents were transferred to another tote and all absorbent material used to clean up the leak were disposed of, along with the damaged tote.  The incident was reported to the Ohio EPA who assigned incident number 1106-31-1922.
column169: The hole had been patched at the origin location.  The persons responsible have been issued written warning letters and one person has been retrained in load securement procedures.

column168: During a routine load check at a rest stop, the driver noticed liquid leaking from the packing around the shaft of the level gauge.  The material was dripping but evaporating as soon as it hit the pavement.  He put a bucket beneath the leak and called his supervisor.  He pulled vacuum on the tanker to stop the leak and put some stop leak material around the area.  He dumped the material collected in the bucket back into the tanker from the dome lid.  The truck then returned to his home terminal where the load was transferred onto another tanker.  The leaking tanker was taken out of service and taken to the maintenance facility which had just repaired the level gauge on May 25, 2011.
column169: The leaking gauge on the tanker had just been repaired by a maintenance facility less than a week before the incident.  The tanker was taken back to that facility for proper repairs.

column17: ROBERTA RAVENSCROFT LEAD CUSTOMER SERVICE AGENT, ALASKA AIRLINES
column168: SHIPPER BROUGHT ITEM OUT TO SEND TO JUNEAU.  AGENT ASKED WHAT HE WAS SENDING, ASKED IF THERE WERE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, AND COMPLETED THE AIRWAY BILL.  SHIPPER ANSWERED, "TANK"; SAID NOTHING WAS HAZARDOUS AND SIGNED THAT THIS SHIPMENT CONTAINS NO DANGEROUS GOODS.  HE LEFT BEFORE SHE WENT TO SCREEN THE BOX.  WHEN SHE SAW THE BOX.  WHEN SHE SAW THE BOX, SHE SAW  THAT THERE WAS A RECTANGULAR BOX WITH UN1956 IN IT.  SHE ASKED ME IF THAT WAS DANGEROUS GOODS, AS SHE IS NOT YET QUALIFIED TO TAKE DANGEROUS GOODS.  I SAID IT LOOKED LIKE IT IS AND TOLD HER TO CALL THE SHIPPER BACK.  THEY WERE CLOSED FOR THE DAY AND SHE LEFT A MESSAGE TO PICK UP TANK BECAUSE IT HAD PRECHARGED UN1956 COMPRESSED AIR IN IT.  ANOTHER AGENT AND I LOOKED INTO WHETHER WE COULD TAKE IT.  I STILL BELIEVED WE COULDN'T AND SHE THOUGHT WE COULD.  SO I PUT THE SHIPMENT ON HOLD AND WE WAITED TO TALK WITH ANOTHER AGENT THIS MORNING.  TERI AND I LOOKED OVER THE IATA AND DOT SP 11592 AND IT APPEARED WE COULD NOT TAKE IT AT LEAST WITHOUT A SHIPPERS DEC.  SO I CALLED AS DANGEROUS GOODS MANAGER AND FURTHER INVESTIGATION DETERMINED WE COULD NOT TAKE IT.  1) THE PROVISION IS FOR HIGHWAY, TRACK OR VESSEL, NOT AIR.  2) THE PRE-PRESSURE AMOUNT IS HIGHER THAN ALLOWED ON PASSENGER AIRCRAFT.

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility. During the course of the trip, the driver conducted a routine load check and identified material leaking from the trailer onto his tires at a rest area. The driver mmediately place an absorbent material down to absorb the free liquid and prevent the spread of the release. Once secured, he notified his home dispatcher and the Danville Fire Department. The fire department contacted a local firm to respond to the spill clean up. Upon arrival the team, utilizing appropriate personal protective equipment, entered the trailer and initiated the removal of containers in order to identify the leaking container. It was discovered that one 5 gallon container was leaking from the bottom seam. The crew placed the leaking containers into a suitable over pack and proceeded to absorb and collect all free liquids. This material was placed into the salvage drums along with all materials used to decontaminate the trailer floor. In addition, the absorbent used to collect the material that escaped from the trailer was collected and this to was placed into the salvage drums for disposal. Once the clean up was complete, the trailer was reloaded and was sent on to the intended waste management facility where the shipment was received and processed for disposal. PA environmental officer Don Farrell was satisfied with the response and clean up.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transporttion, no evidence of leaking was observed. It is believed that the that during transpotation an ajacent pallet gouged the bottom of the container allowing the material to leak from the container. In order to prevent a recurrence, the individuals that offered the shipment for transportation and the driver in posession of the shipment have been re instructed to ensure that each drum is inspected before it is accepted for transportation. Any container that is found to have suspect structural integrity is to be either transferred into a suitable container or placed into a salvage drum for continued transportation.

column168: Cargo not braced to prevent lateral movement resulting in movement to the right side of the container.  Portable tank valve failed, either due to mechanical damage from load shifting or poor maintenance, resulting in spill of class 8 corrosive while in-route on the rail portion of a COFC intermodal load.  Upon arrival at the destination rail head, rail personnel noted the leak, isolated the unit to their hazmat pit and called JB Hunt to dispatch a hazardous materials remediation team.  Spill was remediated; spilled corrosives were contained, absorbed and neutralized and waste properly disposed of by HM subcontractor.  Cause of the spill was determined by NS & JBH safety personnel to be shipper related; results will be shared with the shipper to address any possible future reoccurance.

A BNSF switch crew reported tank car GATX 5817 leaking product in the railyard. GATX 5817 was cordoned-off in the railyard. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders inspected GATX 5817. Responders reported finding the leak source at the liquid eduction line's closure cap area. The closure cap was not fully tightened on its threaded connection. The closure cap's safety or retention chain was pinched in the threaded area by the bottom of the cap; thus interfering with and preventing the closure cap from being fully tightened on its threaded connection. Internal pressure within GATX 5817 was reduced, the closure cap removed and the cap's safety/retention chain repositioned. Teflon tape was applied to the threads of the closure cap and it was reapplied and properly tool tightened by 1700 hrs. MDT, 6/05/2011. Spillage on the shell of GATX 5817 and observed ground spillage was neutralized with baking soda. Response was concluded by 1805 hrs. MDT, 6/05/2011.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: On 6/15/11 at approximately 1310 hours, an Iso container of Tetrahydrofuran (THF)was being off loading at IMTT-Bayonne when a leak was discovered by the IMTT Operator.  The IMTT Operator immediately shut down the operation and depressurized the Iso container which slowed down the leak.  The IMTT Operator placed a 5-gallon pail at the middle of the container to catch the dripping product.  The truck carrying the container was moved to an existing above ground storage tank within IMTT and off loaded.  The truck and empty Iso container were sent back to the trucking company (Linden Bulk Transportation).
column169: IMTT-Bayonne contacted the customer of the product to inform them of the incident. The customer subsequently contacted the transportation company  and will address any mechanical or structural issues with the truck or related components.

column168: Tank car CGTX 30434 in the railyard was reported emanating a product odor and a fresh product stain was observed near its vacuum relief valve (VRV). CGTX 30434 was isolated in the railyard. On 6/16/2011, BNSF hazardous material responders removed the tool tight VRV and inserted a pipe plug in the VRV orifice to a tool tight condition. Visual inspection of the removed VRV revealed that its pressure seal at the bottom of the valve stem was cracked at several locations which prevented a good seal and allowed product to release during rail movement. All spillage evaporated and no ground impact was reported.  The shipper received FRA-11060454 OTMA allowing transport of CGTX 30434 to the consignee's location for unloading.

The shipment was monitored and had no further reaction--it then was accepted into the intended waste disposal facility.

column168: On 06/20/11 Boxley's Jack McCarthy ordered 7500 gallons of Diesel Fuel to be delivered to their Piney River facility on 06/21/11. This incidient occurred on 06/21/11 at approximately 1315 hours at Boxley's Piney River facility. Driver Tim Milton (Foster Fuels' driver)had 7300 gallons to deliver to the Piney River facility. At the time of the release driver Milton was at the end of the unloading process emptying the hoses with the pump still engaged. Product started to spray from the top dome overflow into the containment area and gravel lot. The dome had a lid on it that was not sealed for pressure release and the small openings created a spray effect. Driver Milton immediately stopped the pump and unloading process. Estimate time of the product release is less than one minute. At the time of the release Boxley's storage tank had no means to gauge the liquid capacity of the storage tank. All product release was contained in the containment area and gravel lot, no product reached any public or natural waterway.
column169: Driver Milton is trained in the loading and unloading procedures at Foster Fuels and has unloaded at this facility in the past unloading the amount of product ordered by Boxley. Driver Milton acted according to emergency shut down company procedures.  Boxley is in the process of up grading all of their storage tanks with gauge devices so the liquid content of each tank will be known before the unloading process begans.  Foster Fuels would perfer that the gauge devices be installed before delivery in made in the future at Boxley, if no measuring devices are in place Foster Fuels will require assistance from the facility on amounts of product on hand. No type of equipment failure of Foster Fuels is attributed to this incident.  Foster Fuels will continue to provide training and reviewing incidents like this one for the benefit of all HM employees. This incident has been made a part of driver Milton's employment record.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: Tank car UTLX 208123 was reported expelling product from the top fitting area during normal switching operations in the railyard. Movement was stopped and UTLX 208123 was carefully moved and isolated at a repair track in the railyard. Inspection by a BNSF mechanical responder found the manway closure and all operating valves secure with no visible indications of product leakage. UTLX 208123 was monitored over the weekend with no further indications of any product release. On 6/06/2011, UTLX 208123 was moved from the repair track and switched into other railcars. During this coupling event product was expelled from the pressure relieve device (PRD) atop UTLX 208123. UTLX 208123 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard. Spillage on the tank shell evaporated and no further product release was evident when UTLX 208123 remained motionless. The shipper was notified of the defective PRD and made arrangements to transfer product to trucks and afterwards have the PRD replaced.  Product transfer was completed on 6/15/2011 without further incident. The failed McKenzie 165 psig pressure relief valve (PRV) was replaced in kind on 6/16/2011. The repair responders reported that the failed PRV sustained a broken stem. The PRV spring and associated retainer hardware were not recovered from the inner tank.   The shipper received FRA OTMA FRA-11060442 to transport UTLX 208123 to repair facility for necessary repairs and leakproofness testing.

column169: Investigation discovered that the level gauge was inoperative, which caused the loader to inadvertantly overfill the tanker. column168: A FRA Hazardous Material Safety Inspector reported tank car UTLX 11084 with a loose fill hole securement bolt with product odor and vapor hiss at the fill hole location during his inspection activities in the railyard. A BNSF mechanical carman inspected UTLX 11084 taking no exception at the fill hole location, but repairs to hand rail and air hose support brackets were completed.  On 6/13/2011, UTLX 11084 was reinspected by a BNSF Hazardous Material responder in Fort Worth, TX finding the one securement bolt securing the fill hole locking bar closure not tool tight. The responder applied lubricant to the corroded bolt threads and tool tightened this securement bolt. The slight presence of product odor dissipated and ceased afterwards. No liquid product release was observed. Intact cable seal Bayer 10917 was replaced by BNSF HAZMAT seals numbered 001307, 001362 and 001820 which were applied at the liquid, vapor and fill hole fittings.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Shipment MAWB 615-8331 8034 9PCS/210K (UN1263 Paint related material 1PC/19L,  1PC/26.6L, 1PC/15.2L, 1PC/19L, UN1993 Flammable liquid n.o.s.(contains petroleum  naphtha) 1L UN1866 Resin Solution 1L All packed in one box, UN3077 Environmentally  hazardous substance, solid n.o.s.)contains epoxy resin) 9.2kgs UN1759 Corrosive solid n.o.s.(contains m-xylyenediamine) 6.2kgs All packed in one box, UN1263 Paint  1PC/10L, UN1263 Paint 1PC/25L.    Shipment arrived onboard Kalitta Air flight K4248/27JUN N704CK at Korean Air Cargo BLDG 9 J.F.K. International Airport loaded on pallet PAG2836DHL, positioned in main deck position 16. This was the first pallet to be offloaded from the aircraft and  during unloading the aircraft crew reported faint smell of paint.    The pallet was scheduled to be delivered intact to DHL staff from BLDG 263 at 2030L 27JUN. When loading the pallet onto a dolly for transporting to DHL the staff reported a strong smell and the spillage was discovered. It appears that due to improper tie-down, one piece of the shipment not properly secured stuck another shipment puncturing a hole in the unit.     The pallet on the dolly was relocated to a isolated area and the Port Authority Police were notified. Arrangements were made to have a profeesional outside vendor  do the clean-up. All clean-up material was placed in three spill kit containers for proper disposal.
column169: DHL was advised of the improper build-up and tie-down of this dangerous goods shipment. All information concerning this case will be sent by DHL JDK to origin requesting proper build-up and tie-down procedures be followed and that retraining be given to all staff involved.

column168: DHL Shipment AWB#615-8331-8034 9pcs/210kgs Point of Loading:Leipzig  Description:  -UN1263, Paint related material, 3, PGII, 1fbx19L, 1fbx26.6L, 1fbx15.2L  -UN1263, Paint related material, 3, PGIII, 1fbx19L  -UN1263, Paint, 3, PGIII, 1drumx10L  -UN1263, Paint, 3, PGII, 2drumx25L  -UN1993, Flammable liquid, nos(cont pertoleum Naphtha), 3, PGIII, 1L   UN1866, Resin solution, 3, PGIII, 1L  -UN3077, Environment haz subst, solid nos(cont epoxy resin), 9, PGIII, 9.2kgs   UN1759, Corrosive solid, nos (cont m-xylylenediamine), 8, PGIII, 6.2kgs   All Packed in One    Above was palletized/mixed on unit load device #PAG2836DHL onboard Kalitta Air flight CKS248/N704CK 27JUN2011 arrived at Korean Air Cargo BLDG 9 JFKIA at 1442lcl. This unit was offloaded and stored in Korean housing system at 1615lcl.     At 1930lcl, DHL drivers tried to recover unit for transfer to DHL facility BLDG 263. At 2030lcl, DHL staff reported a strong smell and visual spillage when unit was loading onto dolly for transport.    At 2040lcl, dolly was relocated to an isolated area and Port Authority Police was called at 2115lcl. Spill cleaned by professional outside vendor was done by 0330lcl. Contaminated objects were placed in 3 steel spill kit drums for proper disposal. Duration of contamination was less than 6hours.
column169: DHL was advised of possible improper buildup and tiedown of hazardous materials. DHL JFK local will advance notice to origin for revised retrain procedures on handling dangerous goods.

column168: On 6/22/11 at approximately 0640 hours a Linden Bulk Transportation truck had just completed receiving a full load of Ketrul D-75 and was heading to another area of the terminal to weigh out.  As the truck was approaching the scale, product was discovered leaking from the wash out cap on top of the tanker compartment next to the dome.    IMTT Operations personnel questioned the driver and determined that the wash out cap had not been properly tightened.  Further investigation also showed that product had leaked on the roadway from where the area where the truck was loaded to the current location at the scale.  IMTT Operations personnel contacted EQ-Terminal Services (IMTT's OSRO) to clean up the impacted areas of the roadway.  The Linden driver properly secured the wash out cap and the impacted areas of the tanker compartment were wiped clean.  The truck was weighed and released without further incident.
column169: IMTT-Bayonne contacted the customer of the product to inform them of the incident. The customer subsequently contacted the transportation company  and will address any mechanical or structural issues with the truck or related components.

column168: On 06/03/2011 at 1008 hrs., personnel at the Big Four yard in Russell KY, discovered PPNX 1271, a residue tank car of Ammonia, Anhydrous, leaking from the protective housing. The car was isolated in the rail yard and the shipper, PCS Sales, was notified via CHEMTREC report 2011-06-03-00209. NRC report #978518. Quick Response, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found a leak at the base of the B end liquid line. Quick Response tighten the 4 bolts at the base of the valve but was not able to stop the release. Plug and dike was used to minimize the vapor release until Specialized Professional Services, Inc. (SPSI), arrived to apply a Midland Capping Kit. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Tracey Smith 847-849-4358. SPSI successfully contained the vapor release by capping the valve and then cleaned and purged the car of all residual product. The car was then forwarded to a repair shop by the shipper.     This incident did require a special switching move.    A QA 7.1 Non conformance report is required for this incident.    NARRI Cause Code: 279   NARRI:5 (1+9+2) x (2+0) = 120
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On 6/18/2011 at approx, 1400 hrs., FRA Hazmat Inspector Dedow was inspecting in the CSXT Manville, NJ yard and discovered GATX 66326, a residue tank car of Waste Flammable Liquids, N.O.S., leaking vapor from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the consignee, Veolia Technical Solutions, was contacted via their 24 hour emergency line. The consignee sent a representative to the yard to meet the FRA inspector. The FRA Inspector and CSX Hazmat spoke to Tim Ludwig, Veolia, Transportation Supervisor, regarding the release. The FRA Inspector and the consignee representative determined that 3 of 6 manway bolts were less than tool tight and the gasket was misaligned. The consignee replaced the gasket and made all manway bolts tool tight and the leak was secured. The car was released for transport.     This incident did not require a special switching move.  A QA Non-Conformance report is not required for this incident.    Cause Code: 200  NARRI: 5 (1+3+1) x (2+0) = 50

column168: On 6/21/2011 at approx 1347 hrs., FRA Hazmat Inspector Dedow was inspecting in the CSXT Manville NJ yard and discovered GATX 54507, a residue tank car of Waste Flammable Liquids, N.O.S., leaking vapor from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the consignee,  Veolia Technical Solutions, was notified via CHEMTREC report 2011-06-21-00237. The consignee's representative, Tim Ludwig, responded to the scene and found the 1" vapor valve plug less than tool tight and the valve was closed. The plug was made tool tight, securing the leak, however the ball valve on the 1" line vapor line in the closed position still allowed vapor to pass through.  With the plug tool tight the vapor release stopped.  GATX 54507 is being held awaiting FRA Movement Approval to move the car to the consignee to be cleaned and purged and then will be sent to its home shop to have the 1" vapor valve fixed.    This incident did not require a special switching move.  A QA 7.1 Non-Conformance Report is not required for this incident.    Cause Code: 379  NARRI:  5(1+3+1) x (2+0) = 50

column168: The driver was going west on 1-80 in Lincoln, NE and took Exit 399. While adjusting his CD player, he lost control and went off the off-ramp and turned over, which caused his van trailer to break up, spilling the contents on the  ground. Two mini-bulk tanks of Nutrisphere were in with the load with other products and one tank broke and leaked. The other tank did not leak, so it was picked up. The carrier, United Suppliers, Inc. contacted their spill response contractor, HazMat Response.

column168: On June 21, 2011, a Veolia employee in Schenectady, NY was unloading a trailer of drums using a fork-lift with a double drum grabber attachment. While moving two drums and turning into the receiving trailer, the employee sneezed multiple times and temporarily lost control of the fork-lift.  The fork-lift was accidentally steered towards the receiving trailer door frame.  One of the drums was gouged by a door hinge resulting in a spill of approximately fifteen gallons of material. The gouge in the drum was six inches in length and two inches in width and was located in the upper side of the drum.  The release lasted no more than 20 seconds and the material that leaked was cleaned up and sent to a proper waste disposal facility.  The gouged drum was overpacked and also sent to a proper waste disposal facility.
column169: Veolia employees at Schenectady, NY were trained to cease operating a fork-lift when a bout of sneezing occurs.  Veolia employees were also trained to make wider turns when entering vehicles with a fork-lift.

column162: SENIOR MANAGER HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND COMPLIANCE
column168: Reported that tank car PPGX 3608, load Sodium Hydroxide Solution, was found leaking while being switched at Shreveport yard. Employee David Fontenot was impacted by release and did receive a splatter to his shirt, neck, face, arm area. Employee did remove impacted clothing and rinsed with copious amounts of water. Tank was safely isolated to track 48 south end. Responder found cause of release to be a defective manway gasket.The shipper caused this defect by not properly positioning the nozzle gasket before closing manway.      KCS emergency services were activated to provide for railroad safety qualified services to mitigate this emergency (e.g., special switching for safety isolation, yard service interruption, Critical Incident Desk notifications, emergency response, management oversight, train/yard crew delay, and regulatory notification reports).  KCS Switching Terminal Tariff 8100 Item 860 and KCS Rules Publication Tariff 9011 + 9012 Item 260 may apply.
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. packages or closure defects such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS. The Association of American Railroads (AAR) hazmat inspector (aka BOE inspector) will follow up to all Non Accident Releases (NAR) to assist hazmat shipper with regulatory requirements and training to help prevent recurrence of unsafe transportation conditions.  Also, please reference http://nar.aar.com/ for help understanding and preventing NARs.

The valve was in the closed position, but product was getting past the ball valve.  It was determined the the liquid line valve seat was worn, allowing product to pass.  The shipper contacted a repair facility to replace the valve and re-certify the railcar before movement.

column168: THE FOUR DRUMS WERE SHRINKWRAPPED ON A PALLET.  THERE WERE TWO NAIL HEADS STICKING UP FROM THE PALLET THAT CAUSED THE PUNCTURE.  WHILE UNLOADING THE FREIGHT THE WEIGHT OF THE PALLET CAUSED THE NAIL HEADS TO FULLY PUNCTURE THE DRUM.  THE PRODUCT STARTED TO SMOKE ON THE DOCK DUE TO THE REACTION TO THE CONCRETE AND MOISTURE IN THE AIR.  HALF THE DOCK WAS SHUT DOWN FOR A COUPLE OF HOURS DUE TO VAPORS AND WORK WAS RELOCATED TO THE OTHER END OF THE DOCK.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED AS A PRECAUTION.  ONCE THE RESPONSE TEAM ARRIVED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT LEFT.
column169: NEED TO CHECK PALLETS BETTER FOR NAILS.

column168: While inspecting interchange cars at CN's Markham Yard, East Hazel Crest, IL, a Mechanical Department employee noted product dripping from the bottom outlet valve area of tank car GATX 207562 (R/ LAST CONTAINED AMINES, LIQUID, CORROSIVE, N.O.S.). Car isolated in place and CN's response team responded noting the bottom outlet valve handle pin out, handle down 1/4 turn and product dripping from the between the valve flange and the outlet assembly. Also noted were two of four nuts to the valve flange less than tool tight, allowing product to escape. The valve handle and nuts were properly secured, leak stopped and tank car released to destination.
column169: No additional comments.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: The driver had two totes in his trailer and with one other stop left.  Each tote held 275-gallons.  The driver had one tote in the nose and one tote about 3 pallet widths back tied to the wall with a nylon blue strap.  While in transit the "d" ring on the side of the trailer pulled out of the wall and protruded out of the wall. The pallet slid forward and the "d" ring caused a 2 to 4 inch crack about 1/4 of the way down from the top of the tote.  The Yuma fire dept was called and they deployed a chemical and water boom to contain the spill. And then applied soda ash to neutralize the corrosive. The Corrosive is non toxic.  It is primary reason it is classed corrosive is it highly corrosive to metal especially aluminum
Drum was not blocked or braced, causing 2 pinholes in the middle of the drum. Material leaked out of hole and hardened on outside of drum stopping any more from leaking.

column168: On June 22, 2011, the carrier (Seaboard Marine) was advised by the shipper (Southern Enviro Solutions) that undeclared hazardous materials were stowed inside container SMLU782064-7 (UN1813 POTASSIUM HYDROXIDE, SOLID). The container was on terminal grounds at the time we (Seaboard Marine) received notice that undeclared hazardous cargoes had been loaded.  Upon receiving notice from the shipper we immediately placed a HOLD on the container and prohibited future movement. The shipper was asked to provide the proper documentation describing all the hazardous materials inside of the container. The same day, upon receipt, review and acceptance of the shipping papers, the container was placarded accordingly and subsequently released for transportation
Undeclared hazmat found while screening. Package marked Lithium Batteries-Forbidden for transport aboard Passenger Aircraft. Notified local FAA hazmat agents.

ES&H personnel responded to the site and performed the necessary remediation activities.

column168: A 55-gallon drum of product was damaged during unloading at a loading dock within the Central Transport Terminal.  A small amount of product was released initially inside the trailer.  The terminal then moved the trailer across the parking lot.  When the environmental contractor and the local fire department arrived they could not immediately enter the trailer.  Once the fire department and the environmental contractor could gain access to the trailer the damaged drum was overpacked.  The released product was collected and neutralized.  The trailer and parking lot were decontaminated.  14 drums of impacted materials were containerized for transportation and disposal.

While at a truck stop located at 17980 US Highway 30 East in Grovertown, Indiana the driver noticed a small leak under the right side of the trailer.  The Metropolitan Trucking driver applied absorbent materials to contain the free liquid on the impacted asphalt surface.  Sunpro, Inc. of Elkhart, Indiana was dispatched to perform and investigation of the trailer and complete the site cleanup.    Sunpro, Inc. arrived on-site and opened the trailer doors.  Upon initial inspection, Sunpro, Inc. noticed a lid on the floor underneath an adjacent tote and a small amount of free product on the trailer floor.  Sunpro, Inc. made entry into the trailer utilizing Level C protection.  Sunpro, Inc. applied absorbent material to the free liquid and replaced the missing lid on the leaking tote.
column169: Since the release was accidental and was the result of a missing lid, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  However, Metropolitan Trucking will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: CN mechanical department employee reported an ammonia odor coming from tank car CPDX 102012 (R / LAST CONTAINED: AMMONIA, ANHYDROUS) during a train inspection at the CN Battle Creek Yard, Battle Creek, MI. All appropriate departments notified, tank car isolated. CN response contractor responded noting the tank car's internal pressure at 90 psi and a small amount of product vapor coming the pressure relief valve. Upon further inspection, it was noted that the valve's o-rings were worn allowing a small amount of product vapor to pass . O-rings replaced, valve "bubble" tested and the car was released for movement to destination. Reporting employee later requested medical attention, he was taken to a local medical facility, treated and released without restrictions.

column168: CROP PRODUCTION SERVICES DRIVER WAS DELIVERING A LOADED 1000 GALLON ANHYDROUS AMMONIA NURSE TANK TO A CUSTOMER'S FIELD.  HE WAS TRAVELING ON S.R. 721 ABOUT 1/4 MILE SOUTH OF JONES RD., NORTH OF LAURA, OHIO.  THE DRIVER DROVE OFF THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE ROAD AND OVER-CORRECTED CAUSING THE NURSE TANK TO OVERTURN IN THE DITCH NEXT TO THE ROAD SURFACE.  DURING THE ROLLOVER THE SAFETY CAGE PROTECTING THE TOP VALVES WAS BROKEN OFF, EXPOSING THE FILL VALVES LOCATED ON TOP OF THE TANK.  WHEN THE TANK ROLLED THE VALVES WERE TORN FROM THE TOP OF THE TANK, CAUSING AN UNCONTROLLED RELEASE OF AMMONIA VAPOR AND LIQUID.  LOCAL SAFETY FORCES AND THE OHIO EPA WERE ON SCENE AND IT WAS DECIDED TO ALLOW THE TANK TO EMPTY SINCE IT WAS IN A RURAL AREA AND THE WIND WAS HELPING TO DISPERSE THE VAPOR.  WHEN THE TANK EMPTIED IT WAS UPRIGHTED BY A LOCAL WRECKER SERVICE AND HAULED BACK TO THE CPS LOCATION IN BRADFORD.  THE TANK WAS TAKEN OUT OF SERVICE PENDING INSPECTION AND TESTING BY AN NTIP INSPECTOR.  THE SPILL AREA, 20 FEET LONG BY 4 FEET WIDE, WAS EXCAVATED 8 INCHES DEEP UNDER THE DIRECTION OF CASEY ADAMS, THE ON-SCENE COORDINATOR WITH THE OHIO EPA.  THE MATERIAL WAS THEN LAND APPLIED TO A NEARBY FIELD.  THIS AREA WILL BE BACK-FILLED AND RESEEDED UNDER THE DIRECTION OF ODOT, PERMIT NUMBER 7-179-11.

column168: After a transfer of sulfuric acid between railcar TILX 100524 and CTL Trailer# 23088 took place, product was observed leaking running down the side of the railcar.  The railcar remained set up after first transfer.  A Loader, with the required PPE, climbed to the top up the railcar and identified the product tee fitting as being loose.  Pressure inside the railcar forced liquid out from around the loose fitting.  Several pictures were taken of the spill and the leaking tee fitting.  Approximately 2 gallons of product leaked from the railcar to the 1'x 1" square gravel area beside the track. No product entered the storm drain. Lime was used to neutralize the acid. All clean up material was put into containers and labeled.
column169: ROOT CAUSE:   1. The railcar was not depressurized prior to the Loader leaving the transfer area unattended because it was not specifically stated in the Site-Specific Procedure (SSP).   2. The pipe connection was not properly tool tight when the transfer was originally set-up due to wear and tear of the fitting.     3. The stainless steel pipe tee was not properly inspected to identify excessive wear before being utilized for the transfer.     CORRECTIVE ACTIONS:   1. Add warning to SSP 3025-002 to reflect that railcars should be depressurized if there isn’t another trailer readily available to load.   2. Terminal will inspect and remove from service all fittings and connections that may be damaged or have excessive wear and tear from use.

column168: Entrained top-stacked 53 foot intermodal container CSXU 632694 was leaking an unknown substance on the outside of the container below it, as reported during a BNSF inbound train inspection. The rail flatcar that CSXU 632694 was riding upon was setout of the train for further inspection. CSXU 632694 was deramped/grounded at the railyard's containment area. BNSF contract responders inspecting the interior of CSXU 632694 reported finding no blocking and bracing of 10 pallets of hazardous material drums loaded four drums per pallet located at the nose of this container. The drums were bound by a single securement banding around the four drum set on each pallet. These drums were the only lading inside CSXU 632694, therefore creating a huge void from the container's nose area to the rear doorway. Twelve steel 55 gallon drums (UN 1A1/Y1.4/150/1107) had leaked contents with six of these drums almost releasing their entire contents. All drums appeared distressed to some degree with top and bottom drum heads bulging along with some drum sidewalls nicked and abraded. The leaking drums had bottom head stress cracks with pinhole leaks in the crack line. Holes in the leaking drums were patched with epoxy where appropriate and placed into over-pack drums. All other drums were also placed into over-pack drums. Impacted soils near CSXU 632694 were shoveled into poly bags and placed into a recovery drum. The bottom intermodal container that sustained product leakage on its exterior was cleaned. The interior of the CSXU 632694 was cleaned of spillage. Expended cleaning supplies were placed into recovery drums. All 40 over-pack drums along with all recovery drums were returned inside CSXU 632694 properly blocked and braced for further transport.     The labeling on these imported drums indicated that the product manufacturer and distributer was PSV Services SRL in Tornaco (NO), Italy. It appears that this drum shipment was reloaded into CSXU 632694 after their arrival in Miami, FL (Port of Entry).
column169: Ensure shipper inspects non-bulk hazardous material shipment packages for damages and transport worthiness prior to loading them into intermodal containers with the appropriate blocking and bracing also applied.

column162: SENIOR MANAGER HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND COMPLIANCE
column168: Shreveport yard reported to CID that ACFX 200118, residue: Last Contained Combustible Liquid, N.O.S., Crude Oil, was discovered leaking (dripping) from the bottom outlet valve while in Track 15. The CID made required Louisiana State Police notification. Found the top operated bottom outlet valve (BOV) completely open. Incident mitigated by closing the BOV.  Also, found the BOV secondary closure cap loose, simply threaded on BOV. The BOV cap was then secured tool tight. Approximately 2 gallons released from unsecured BOV and cap. The other closures were checked and the liquid and vapor lines were found closed and secondary plugs tool tight. However, the manway cover was found less than tool tight. The manway gasket was inspected and found in satisfactory condition and the residue heel was found to be 10 inches wide.     KCS emergency services were activated to provide for railroad safety qualified services to mitigate this emergency (e.g., special switching for safety isolation, yard service interruption, Critical Incident Desk notifications, emergency response, management oversight, train/yard crew delay, and regulatory notification reports).  KCS Switching Terminal Tariff 8100 Item 860 and KCS Rules Publication Tariff 9011 + 9012 Item 260 may apply.    Item 27, amount in package, was estimated by f5800.1 report preparer because: shipper only provided bulk quantity on shipping paper, as 1 Tank Car, per PHMSA DOT requirements; and because the PHMSA DOT e-system requires data in this field to match the same units used in the capacity field.    The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. packages or closure defects such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS. The Association of American Railroads (AAR) hazmat inspector (aka BOE inspector) will follow up to all Non Accident Releases (NAR) to assist hazmat shipper with regulatory requirements and training to help prevent recurrence of unsafe transportation conditions.  Also, please reference http://nar.aar.com/ for help understanding and preventing NARs.

column168: Tank car TILX 193391 was reported leaking from the manway closure area during movement in the railyard. Movement was stopped and TILX 193391 was cordoned-off in the railyard. TILX 193391 did not release product while it remained motionless. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspected TILX 193391 and reported finding all manway securement bolts tool tight, but the manway gasket was missing. No ground spillage from this product release was reported. A response contractor was summoned to clean the shell of TILX 193391 and apply a new manway gasket. On 6/22/2011 the responders cleaned the spillage off of TILX 193391 and returned the morning of 6/23/2011 to apply a replacement manway gasket. The new manway gasket was installed and the manway closure resecured by 0820 hrs. MDT, 6/23/2011.

column162: SENIOR MANAGER HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND COMPLIANCE
column168: Baton Rouge yard reported to KCS Critical Incident Desk (CID) that tank car NATX 210016, Residue: Last Contained Hydrochloric Acid, was found venting a small about of vapor fumes from the flangable disk housing while being switched. The CID notified the Louisiana State Police per regulatory requirement. Also, CID notified shipper via Chemtrec.    Responders reported that venting release sourced from frangible disk housing. The house bolts was tightened to stop the release. Each bolt was tightened approximately  turn. There was no liquid lading released, only a very small about of vapor/fume. The disk was inspected from the top side and found to be in good condition. This condition would have been very difficult for an unloading facility to discover and should have been detected and corrected at the load origin.     An addition tank car, NATX 210012, Residue: Last Contained Hydrochloric Acid, was also inspected as a suspect leaker. No leak could be identified on this car. All fitting where tightened as a precaution. No fittings were found loose or actively leaking.    Item 27, amount in package, was estimated by f5800.1 report preparer because: shipper only provided bulk quantity on shipping paper, as 1 Tank Car, per PHMSA DOT requirements; and because the PHMSA DOT e-system requires data in this field to match the same units used in the capacity field.    Item 19: No liquid product was released by this car. Only product odor vapors were released. PHMSA DOT reporting system will not allow reporting vapor release from a liquid commodity. Therefore this minor vapor release is reported as 0.01 gallon.    Shipper has been so advised that, for business unit planning, that all 3rd party costs associated with this incident, along with special switch charges will be invoiced to Shipper of record FSTI Inc. under KCS Switching Terminal Tariff 8100 Item 860 and KCS Rules Publication Tariff 9011 + 9012 Item 260.

column168: While preparing the second half a ferric sulfate transfer, approximately twenty gallons of product was released onto the concrete after the loader opened the inlet valve on the back of trailer 581 without properly attaching the other end of the hose to railcar TCIX 21106.  The loader quickly closed the trailer valve and called code yellow over the radio. Terminal personnel reacted promptly and placed lime onto the release to neutralize and absorb the product. Absorbent pads were placed over the area as well to further help with the cleanup of the material. Later the product was cleaned up and contained for disposal at a later date.
column169: ROOT CAUSES:   1. Loader failed to install the product transfer hose to the railcar due to the fact that he was aggravated and distracted after having a disagreement with a fellow employee.   2. Verifier failed to inspect the transfer set up and subsequently “pencil whipped” the Work Order by signing off as having verified prior to inspecting transfer set up.  3. Loader failed to install plug on railcar side of the product transfer hose after 1st part of split load. The cap was not in the vicinity of the product hose.      CORRECTIVE ACTIONS:   1. Retraining to take place to include:   a. Training the Loader and Verifier on SSP 3025-002 Transferring Corrosive via Blower Pac/Air Compressor.   b. Training the Verifier on Kinder Morgan’s Verification policy.  c. Training Loader to ensure all liquid hoses are capped when not in use.   2. Increase MBWA to ensure all steps of the verification policy is followed.    3. Increase MBWA to ensure all hoses are capped when not being used in the transfer process.

column168: While off-loading material at the Veolia facility located in Menomonee Falls, WI, a Veolia employee noticed a small wet spot on the trailer floor. Further investigation revealed that there was a 55 gallon steel drum that had developed a small leak as a result of what appeared to be small puncture that could have come from a fork lift. The drum was subsequently placed into a salvage drum and absorbent was used to clean up the spilled solvent and placed into the salvage drum.
column169: This incident was reviewed with field service employees as well as facility employees emphasizing the need to ensure the condition of containers prior to shipment as well as the need to use care when using mechanical means to move containers.

column168: Vehicle involved in roll-over accident.  Chemtrec (report number 2011-06-02-00056) advised Service Center Manager on scene that it was safe for Con-way employees to clean up spill, no hazmat team was necessary.      Trailer righted and tow company to tow to nearest facility.  Highway patrol stopped tow vehicle due to leakage from trailer approximately 1 gallon are estimated to have leaked inside of trailer, part of which leaked out of trailer onto road and shoulder creating a spill reported to be 6 inches by 6 inches.    Fire departments (Rochester and Claremont, report number unknown) determined that there should be no further leakage of material and allowed the tow company to continue to facility in Owatonna, MN.    Trailer cleaned at facility by employees.  Damaged material moved to salvage area for later disposal. Remainder of freight minus 1 piece reported damaged, delivered to consignee.
column169: Safety policy currrently in place to reduce accidents and injuries.    Spill reporting process failed.  Added a reminder to report spills to the standard work instructions for the accident call center personnel.

column168: Driver was transferring 2404 gallons from the cargo tank to a 4000 customer storage tank with 1000 gallons in it to start.    When he had offloaded about 800 gallons, he noticed some product start to come out of the overflow on the tank.  He immediately shut down to minimize the spill to 1 qt.  Driver was unaware that there were two tanks that were to fill and a valve was closed between them. The valve was opened and delivery was completed without incident.
column169: There should have been better directions about the valve between the two tanks.

column168: DON MAGILL WAS CALLED TO 91 DOOR FOR A LEAKING HAZMAT PACKAGE. WEARING PROPER PPE AND USING THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEETS, THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP AND RETURNED TO THE DMP FOR PROCESSING INTO THE DMP.
column169: NO COMMENT PROVIDED.

column168: AT 1830 HOURS A DESIGNATED RESPONDER ARRIVED AT A SPILL ON THE PACKAGE SECONDARY SORTING SLIDE.  THERE WAS A SMALL PUDDLE UNDER AND PARTIALLY SURROUNDING THE PACKAGE (A 15*15*17 IN DOUBLE WALL 51 LBS/IN EDGE CRUSH TEST FIBREBOARD BOX.)  THE PACKAGE WAS FOUND ON ITS SIDE, NOT UPRIGHT.  A PRIMARY INSPECTION SHOWED NO SIGNS OF EXTERNAL CARTON DAMAGE.  THE SPILLED ACETONE WAS CLEANED AND CONTAINED.  AFTER TRANSPORTING THE PACKAGE TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA AN INTERNAL INSPECTION WAS DONE REVEALING THAT 1 OF THE 4-L GLASS JUGS HAD CRACKED AND SHATTERED RELEASING ITS CONTENTS.  THE OTHER THREE CONTAINERS WERE COVERED WITH RESIDUE.  THE PACKING MATERIAL (CORRUGATED FIBER BOARD) WAS ONLY 1/2IN THICK ON THE SIDES AND BOTTOM ALLOWING THE BREAKAGE TO OCCUR.  THE CONTAMINATED MATERIAL WAS PROCESSED THROUGH THE UPS DMP.
column169: NO COMMENT PROVIDED.

column168: RESPONDER ARRIVED AT THE HAZMAT AND NOTICED THAT THE HAZMAT WAS WET AT THE BOTTOM.  NOTIFIED THE DMP CAGE AND BROUGHT IT BACK TO BE PROPCESSED THROUGH DMP.
column169: NO COMMENT PROVIDED.

column168: THE PACKAGE WAS UNLOADED AT A FEEDER AT WHICH TIME IT WAS NOTICED THAT A SIDE OF THE BOX WAS WET.  PRIOR TO TRANSPORT TO OUR CENTER THERE WAS CLEAR TAPE USED TO COVER UP THE WET PORTION OF THE BOX.  THE LIQUID HAD BUILD UP UNDERNEATH THE TAPE.  PROGRESS OF THE PACKAGE WAS STOPPED AND I, THE RMP, RESPONDED TO THE PACKAGE IN FULL PPE.  I OPENED THE BOX FOR INSPECTION AND SAW THAT A LITTLE LESS THAN HALF THE CONTENTS OF THE PLASTIC BOTTLE HAD LEAKED OUT AND THAT THE CAP WAS LOOSE. THE REMAINING LIQUID WAS SOLIDIFIED.
column169: RESPONDERS WHO NOTICE A WET PACKAGE WITH A HAZMAT LABEL SHOULD INVESTIGATE IT INSTEAD OF ATTEMPTING TO COVER IT UP.

I USED THE DECISION TREE AND THE RESPONSE SHEET FOR CORROSIVE MATERIAL.  I COLLECTED THE DAMAGED MATERIAL.  I USED SODIUM BICARBONATE WHERE THE DRY CHEMICAL WAS GELING UP AND TURNING LIQUID.  I BOUGHT ALL DAMAGE MATERIAL BACK TO THE DMP AREA FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.  I GOT A MSDS FOR THE EMPOYLEE WHO WAS EXPOSED.  THE DAMAGE PACKAGE WAS IMPROPERLY PACKAGE.  THE INSIDE CONTENTS WERE A PAPER BAG THAT RIPPED OPEN.  NO INNER PACKING MATERIAL.

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: Human error. NO PACKAGING FAILURE.  Following unloading of DOT 407 specification trailer, driver followed normal procedure of opening upper vent valve to depressurize tank (tank is pressurized with compressed air prior to unloading in order to push product off).  Driver failed to close upper vent valve prior to leaving unloading facility (New Wales).  Approximately 45 minutes later, upon loading tank with sulfuric acid, driver departed loading facility (South Pierce) with upper vent valve open. Upon agitation with vehicle movement, sulfuric acid sloshed out of open upper vent valve and out the 2 inch discharge at the bottom of trailer creating approximately a 1/2 mile intermittant trail (6-8" wide)of sulfuric acid along West Bound County Rd 630. Driver noticed the spillage when he stopped at the first set of RR tracks.  CR 630 is lightly travelled, and Polk County Sheriff's Department and SWS Environmental responded and neutralized spill with soda ash.  Contaminated Soda Ash was removed and disposed of.  No waterways or drainage systems were impacted.
column169: This spill was 100% driver error.  We coordinated with shipper to stand down from the operation for an entire day on which we conducted extensive safety and procedural training with all drivers with specific focus on this incident.

Responders reported that the Salco Quick Inspect safety vent with its Quick Inspect Body (QIB) and its top inspection cap (plug) not applied, but still attached to the safety vent assembly. The frangible disc was also missing from the interior of this safety vent. The responders properly applied a new 165 psig frangible disc into the safety vent. The QIB with top inspection cap (plug) was applied and appropriately tightened. All observed spillage was neutralized and no ground impact from spillage was reported.

column168: On June 22, 2011, the carrier (Seaboard Marine) was advised by the Freight Forwarder (Dangerous Goods At MIA) that undeclared hazardous materials were stowed inside container SMLU 784736-0 (UN1044 Fire Extinguishers). column169: BE AWARE OF SURROUNDINGS!  RETRAINING ON SAFE USE AND OPERATION OF THE FORKLIFT.  WHEN ENTERING TRAILERS WITH PAILS, DRUMS OR TOTES LOADED AND HIDDEN BEHIND FREIGHT, WHEN USING BLADES, ESPECIALLY THE LONG BLADES, ENTER WITH CAUTION TO AVOID PUNCTURING THE VARIOUS PACKAGES.  FREIGHT PLACED ON DOCK MUST BE SECURED AND PROPERLY BLOCKED AND SHROUDED TO AVOID EASY PUNCTURING FROM OTHER FREIGHT OR FORKLIFT.  DISCUSS DURING PRESHIFT ON THE SAFETY OF DOCKING, REMOVING AND TRANSFERRING CHEMICAL, LIQUID AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  BEING AWARE OF SURROUNDINGS WHEN WORKING. ON THE DOCK AND WHILE TRANSFERRING PACKAGES OF CHEMICALS, LIQUIDS OR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS!  PAILS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, MTY PALLETS AND PLYWOOD TO PREVENT EASY DAMAGE AND PUNCTURING.

column168: A shipment of 5 IBCs containing UN1230 - Methyl Alcohol were loaded in Carencro LA for shipment to Venice LA without incident or evidence of any problems. Upon arrival at destination, the carrier notified shipper that one of the IBC's developed a small drip. Response contractor was engaged to repond and transfer the contents into drums for safe transport. Duration of the response was approximately 5 hours. No injuries, exposures nor road closures resulted from this incident.    Subject IBC was built 11/2007, was in current UN test, and was inspected prior to fill.    Post incident inspection and testing of the IBC revealed a hairline crack in the weld fusing the 2"NPT discharge nipple to the bottom head of the tank. Close inspection of the valvetrain showed a proper valve and plumbing configuration as well as proper alignment within the outer tank edge for protection. There was no evidence of impact to the valve or tank area.
column169: In this case, given that the tank utilized was in test, in good condition, showed no evidence of any leakage at time of fill and shipping, and showed no evidence of any impacts or damage during shipping it is believed that road vibration may have played a role in the failure.    As a result, shipper is exploring the feasibility of use of certain field  applicable non destructive testing (NDT) procedures in order to provide a better ability to visually inspect IBC welds for possible signs of stress that may be difficult or impossible to detect via normal means. If possible / feasible, this would occur in addition to the UN leakproofness test as prescribed in 49CFR178.813

column168: In preparation for performing work at the NRD site in Grand Island, NY, a transport trailer containing mobile shipping equipment was sent from Carlsbad, NM to NRD. The trailer contains equipment such as work platforms, lifting and handling components, and helium leak testing components. This type of shipment is routine, and is normally performed by one of the two commercial carriers on contract to the DOE at the Waste Isolation Pilot Plant (WIPP). In this instance, the carriers were unavailable, so the WIPP transportation group requested a procurement specialist to obtain the services of a third commercial carrier to transport this equipment. An accurate hazardous material bill of lading (BOL) was provided to the procurement specialist, who in turn provided it to the third commercial carrier. This draft BOL identified the shipment as containing hazardous materials (4 pressurized gas cylinders, 2 of helium, and 2 of nitrogen, all properly labeled, marked and secured). The procurement specialist discussed the presence of the cylinders with the carrier when the draft BOL was provided. The carrier created their own BOL, but in doing so, inadvertently omitted the gas cylinder information and thus identified the shipment as containing no hazardous materials, and returned it to the procurement specialist for signature. The procurement specialist, having discussed the matter with the carrier, assumed that the documentation was correct, and signed the carrier BOL. The carrier BOL was not given to the WIPP Transportation group for review or signature due to the use of an outdated revision of a procedure by the procurement specialist who assumed a Transportation review was unnecessary.
column169: The following measures have been taken to prevent recurrence: Revisions will be processed to procedures to assure that the authority to sign BOLs is assigned to properly trained individuals for both hazardous and non hazardous shipments; users of applicable procedures will be provided with current revisions; roles and responsibilities will be defined in a new procedure to emphasize inter-departmental responsibilities and authorities.

column168: Approximately 20 gallons of Xylene overflowed from compartment #5 of Nexeo trailer 35629.  The trailer was in the process of a transload from railcar CTCX 731251.  Upon investigation, the spill began when the loader was purging line from the railcar to the trailer with air creating a surge or a bubble that erupted over the opening. The compartment holds 2450 gallons and 2400 gallons were loaded before purging the line.  A spill pan was placed under the overflow hoses but due to the mounting of the hoses, overflow bounced off the inside of the back bumper causing it to miss the spill pan.  Some product impacted the spill pan, while the remaining product was contained in sand and absorb all material.  No product impacted the storm drain. Jeff Mitchell from Mecklenburg County Water Quality verified the same.
column169: ROOT CAUSES:  1. The experienced Loader believed he could load 2400 gallons of product into a compartment that has a capacity of 2450 gallons while having sufficient headroom for blowback.  Due to the high level of product, when the line was purged, an estimated thirty gallons of residual product and a surge of air created a bubble causing product to spill out of the manway.    2. There are no written or specified outage amounts for trailers.     CORRECTIVE ACTIONS:  1. Management must determine the proper outage amount for the filling of liquid trailers.    2. Develop training for flammable product release response to include the use of proper tools such as aluminum shovels.    3. Request that TRANSFLO communicate the Carrier make alterations to the configuration of overflow tubes to better direct product into the spill pan.

column17: BETTER MANAGEMENT CORPORATION OF OHIO, INC.
column168: This writer received a call at approximately 12:45 p.m. from Dump & Roll-Off Division independent contractor William Murphy. According to Mr. Murphy, he was assisting fellow Dump & Roll-Off Division independent contractor David Patterson with a hazardous substance spill in Wapakoneta, OH. According to Mr. Murphy, Mr. Patterson loaded K061 furnace dust at Steel Dynamics, Inc. in Butler, IN on Tuesday, June 14, 2011 at approximately 4:30 a.m. While loading Mr. Murphy and Mr. Patterson noticed that they may be over on the drive axles when Mr. Patterson would have to fuel. Mr. Patterson fueled his tractor at the TA Truck Stop in Wapakoneta, Ohio. Ater fueling, Mr. Patterson raised the dump body of D322 so he could shift some of the load to the rear of the trailer. However, while raising the dump body, some of the dust broke loose and spilled over the tailgate of the trailer between the top and the tarp. According the Mr. Murphy, approximately 500-700 pounds of the product ended up on the asphalt of the parking lot directly behind the trailer. In his estimation, the spill covered an area of approximately three feet by 4 feet and  making a pile approximately two feet high. He stated they swept the dust into a  pile and covered the pile with a tarp to keep it from blowing due to breezy  conditions. Mr. Murphy was instructed to inform the management of the TA Truck  Stop and call the local authorities. This writer asked for and received the  Emergency Response Telephone number from the UHWM, UHWM # and the  amount of the product loaded.
column169: ALL DRIVERS ARE BEING INSTRUCTED TO NOT, UNDER ANY CIRCUMSTANCES, SHIFT A LOAD IN A TRAILER BY LIFTING THE DUMP BED. ALL DRIVERS AND INPENDENTENT CONTRACTORS ARE BEING TOLD TO SHIFT THE LOAD VIA ALTERNATE METHODS. THIS WILL BE COMMUNICATED VIA MEMORANDUMS, SAFETY MEETING  AND ORIENTATION.

column168: At the beggining of the offloading process on 6/29/11, product began to leak out of the base of the pump. column169: During the investigation it was realized that the pump in question was recently re-installed after being removed by a third party contactor for preventative maintenance. The pump was re-installed by the contractor but was not set in place properly with the proper seal. The pump was tagged out of service and the contractor returned with a new seal to properly re-install the pump.     This contractor was not used prior to this incident. Moving forward all contractors will be approved prior to beggining work to ensure they are up to Kinder Morgan standards.

column168: THE SEMI-TRACTOR TRAILER INVOLVED WAS TRAVELING SOUTH ONA FOUR LANE NON-DIVIDED HIGHWAY AT POSTED SPEED WHEN THE DRIVER REACHED TO THE FLOOR TO PICK UP A CHARGER CORD. WHILE LEANING TO HIS RIGHT, THE DRIVER SLIGHTLY PULLED THE STEERING WHEEL, ALSO TO THE RIGHT, CAUSING THE VEHICLE TO DROP OFF THE EDGE OF THE PAVEMENT. THE VEHICLE THEN STRUCK A CEMENT CULVERT, WHICH PREVENTED A POSSIBLE RETURN TO THE ROADWAY. THIS CAUSED THE VEHICLE TO DROP INTO THE DITCH AS IT ROLLED TO A STOP AT A 45 DEGREE ANGLE AGAINST THE DIRT BANK. THE TOTAL TRAVEL DISTANCE FROM DROP OFF POINT TO REST POINT WAS 145 FEET. ALL EMERGENCY SERVICES WERE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED, AS THE WITNESS TO THE ACCIDENT WAS AN ON-DUTY LOCAL POLICE OFFICER WHO WAS TRAVELING NORTH AT THE TIME. THE DRIVER OF THE ROLLED VEHICLE CLIMBED FROM THE CAB ON HIS OWN, AND CALLED MY OFFICE AS HE WAS HE WAS EVALUATING THE SITUATION TO RELAY AS MUCH NEEDED INFORMATION AS POSSIBLE. AFTER I COLLECTED ALL THE INFORMATION EEDED, I NOTIFIED THE NRC AND THE DEP. THE ROLLED TRAILER SUSTAINED COSMETIC DAMAGE TO THE OUT SKIN AND INSULATION WITH "NO" CRACKS OR FRACUTES TO THE TANK OR DAMAGE TO THE REAR UNLOADING VALVE. THE MANHOLE AREA ON TOP OF THE TRAILER WAS NOT COMPROMISED. THERE WERE NO PACKAGE OR VALVE FAILURE POINTS. PRODUCT BEGAN TO FLOW THRU THE VENT ASSEMBLY INTO THE DOME BOX AND TRAVELED THROUGH THE OVERFLOW TUBE INTO THE DITCH UNDER THE TRAILER FOR APPROXIMATELY 30 MINUTES AT THE RATE OF A WATER HOSE FLOW, UNTIL IT LEVELED OFF INSIDE THE TRAILER. ONE LOAD OF DIRT WAS DUMPED AT EAH END OF THE VEHICLE WHICH CONTAINED THE SPILLED PRODUCT WITHIN THE LENGTH OF THE UNIT. AFTER THE SPILLED PRODUCT IN THE DITCH COOLED AND SOLIDIFIED, IT WAS EASILY REMOVED AND HAULED AWAY FROM THE SITE.
column169: OUR COMPANY MAKES THE GREATEST EFFORT TO TRAIN OUR DRIVERS TO AVOID ANY AND ALL DISTRACTIONS. THEY MUST REALIZE THAT IT ONLY TAKES A SPLIT SECOND TO CREATE A SITUATION DUE TO HUMAN ERROR, THAT SHIFTS CONTROL OF THE VEHICLE THEY ARE DRIVING, TO THE LIQUID PRODUCT THAT THEY ARE TRANSPORTING, WHICH IS CONSTANTLY MOVING IN ALL DIRECTIONS, TO CAUSE A DANGEROUS SITUATION OR ACCIDENT. THE DRIVER MUST REMAIN ALERT AND BE IN COMPLETE CONTROL AT ALL TIMES WHILE OPERATING A COMMERCIAL MOTOR VEHICLE. IF A DISTRACTION DOES OCCUR, AND ONE WILL, THEY SHOULD THEN FIND THE NEAREST SAFE PARKING AREA AND DEAL WITH IT AT THAT TIME IF IT'S AN URGENCY.

column42: RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL, EXCEPTED PACKAGE - ARTICLES MANUFACTURED FROM NATURAL OR DEPLETED URANIUM OR NATURAL THORIUM
column168: An order was placed for 100 radiotherapy seeds at Brigham and Women’s Hospital for treatment. This order was an immediate need as they had a patient going in for surgery the next day. We rerouted a shipment on June 2, 2011 meant for another site and in doing so we inadvertently shipped them ten (10) seeds for the procedure instead of the hundred (100) that they requested. Both packages of seeds are packaged in our standard Type A package from our distributor in Germany to ensure safe transport overseas. While investigating how this mishap occurred, our Holland office asked one of our account managers to send back the labels from the box and any additional hazardous goods documents. The account manager spoke with both the hospital and a salesman in the area. On June 24, 2011, a Nucletron salesman went to Brigham and Women’s Hospital and collected the package that the salesman understood contained only the documents in question. He then took the package to a nearby mail box store and sent the package back the US Nucletron office. The mailbox store shipped it without the necessary markings and the box arrived undamaged and unopened in the Nucletron office in Columbia, MD on June 28, 2011.   The package was opened in the US office, and an approved stainless steel shielded container was discovered. From the information on the label it was determined that it contained ten (10) radioactive seeds. The shielded container for the radioactive seeds was never opened as the pictures show the autoclave bag has not been tampered with. As soon as the package was opened, a wipe test and two readings were taken.   Two dose rate readings were taken from outside the dispose container and a wipe test was conducted: the results could not distinguish from background (0) reading taken on most sensitive setting. Below are the meter identification and calibration due dates.   Meter ID: Ludlum 165951   Calibration Due Date:6/14/12   Meter ID: Ludlum 170195   Calibration Due Date: 2/23/12   Wipe Test: Inspector 08558   Calibration Due Date: 6/14/12
column169: Moving forward, the shipment of radioactive materials will only be undertaken on the instruction of the radiation safety officer or equivalent in the specific region of the shipment. The management team in the US has made this decision and it will be communicated to the field in an email and phone call for all field service engineers and sales associates in the coming days. This communication will also be added to new hire training and radiation safety training.

column168: On 7/11/2011 at approximately 1800, the foreman noticed ethanol leaking from the top of the first railcar located at 1 siding B track (opposite road side). The path of the ethanol ran down the sides to the ground ofthe railcar (NATX-364454) from shipper Valero Marketing with Hazmat Number 050409 001 008RT. The spill left a 4 foot wide visible path down the sides of the tank car. The drip pan under the rail car caught a majority of the ethanol, but it overflowed and product impacted the soil. Product also missed the drip pan and directly impacted the soil directly surrounding the drip pan. The total square footage of impacted soil is approximately 8 feet. The estimated amount of ethanol that impacted the soil is 25 gallons. The RQ for ethanol is 15 gallons.    Further investigation indicated that the check valve located behind the block valve at spot 5B where the car was connected didn't hold. The release occurred because of a faulty check valve. The ethanol product specifically spilled through a 1" valve on top of the railcar. No one was impacted by product and all PPE was properly worn during the incident.    Any mitigation actions taken at the time of the incident. The block valve on the line connected to the product hose was closed immediately, stopping the product from continuing to fill the rail car. The impacted rock and soil was shoveled and placed into a labeled satellite drum. The block valve that connects to the block valve was then locked out. The depth of ethanol contamination in the soil and rocks underneath the rail car was approximately 4 inches. All impacted soil and rocks were excavated and stored in a 55-gallon drum. One 55-gallon drum was generated from this spill. The drum was labeled as hazardous waste and was placed in the final storage area awaiting shipment to approved RCRA facility.
column169: Cleanup is considered complete and no further soil remediation is planned. Beginning  7/13/11 all check valves that have similar application will be inspected for quality and more comprehensive preventive maintenance program will be implemented.

MOST OF THE ANHYDROUS AMMONIA WAS RELEASED WITHIN 5 HOURS, HOWEVER, THE RELIEF VALVE CONTINUED TO RELEASE A SMALL AMOUNT INTO THE NEXT DAY.

Quality Auto Body recovered the product at the scene and also the vehicles.Polar Bear Trucking representitives arrived at the scene approx 35 min after the initial report to our offices.
column169: Based on all reports , the driver of the truck vehicle was given no time to respond to the sudden and careless actions of the car vehicle driver.I would recommend a traffic light at the intersection of Rt 32 and Orrs Mills Rd. The dome covers of the tank held all but one.i would recommend a double clap on the dome covers with an outter protection containment ballon around the seal.

column168: XHR terminal Service Center Manager:  It is assumed that a "Safe Stack" (rack system) strap stuck into the top of the tote at some point in transit.  Liquid spilled out of the IBC in transit from this small hole that was created.  Spill discovered at delivery point which was a mix of residential and light industrial.      First responder on scene, a volunteer firefighter called in the hazardous materials incident, notifying multiple fire departments.  In addition to these personnel, three persons from DEP were on scene.      Hazmat clean-up vendor, TMS, unable to respond for approximately 1.5 hours. Public emergency response personnel would not allow them to enter scene.  It is possible that this is due to the technical chemical name on the shipping paper (2,2-dibromo-2-cyanoacetamide) not matching the name on the MSDS.  The name listed on this report is the name of the chemical from the MSDS.  The amount spilled was between 1.5 gallons and 4 gallons. This street was closed for approximately 1 hour.  Vendor contained and cleaned spill, then left the scene.    Will update report with agency report numbers as well as total costs as soon as it is feasible.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING A LEAK WAS DISCOVERED INSIDE OF TRAILER. THE FREE LIQUID WAS THOUGHT TO BE SOAP, SO THE TRAILER WAS WASHED OUT. UPON FURTHER INSPECTION OF THE TRAILER A LEAKING CARTON OF CORROSIVE LIQUID, BASIC, INORGANIC, N.O.S WAS DISCOVERED. THE TRAILER WAS ISOLATED AND BY SQAURED OF MADISON, WISCONSIN WAS DISPATCHED TO COMPLETE FURTHER INSPECTION OF THE TRAILER.    CT SQUARED ARRIVED ON-SITE AND COMPLETED A SITE ASSESSMENT. THE MATERIAL THAT WAS WASHED OUT OF THE TRAILER IMPACTED A STORMWATER COLLECTION GRATE. THE STORMWATER COLLECTION GRATE WAS INSPECTED AND IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE FREE LIQUID WAS NOT RECOVERABLE. BT SQUARED INSPECTED THE TRAILER AND DISCOVERED SIX (6) LEAKING ONE-GALLON PLASTIC JUGS. THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE APPEARED TO BE A PACKAGING FAILURE. THE LEAKING CONTAINERS WERE PLACED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM FOR DISPOSAL. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING FURTHER INSTRUCTIONS. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.
column169: SINCE THE RELEASE WAS ACCIDENTAL, NO PLANS CURRENTLY EXIST TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. HOWEVER, IVESCO, LLC WILL CONTINUE TO REINFORCE SAFETY GUIDELINES AND HANDLING PROCEDURES TO ALL PERSONNEL.

The driver arrived at the customer for off loading. The plant operator started applying nitrogen pressure to the trailer to off load the product. Once the pressure was applied, the trailer started leaking from under the belly of the trailer, through the outer skin. The operator then shut off and depressured the trailer and the trailer stopped leaking. The spill was contained and cleaned up by the plant operator. Another unit was sent to the plant where the product was transferred into. Once the leaking trailer was cleaned and inspected, it was found to have cracks on the left and right side of the ring and bolster area in front of the tandems of the trailer. They were repaired and the trailer was hydro tested for leaks, with no leaks present after testing. Length of cracks was not noted upon repairs being made.
